  <h2 id="who-avoid">Who Should Not Try Intermittent Fasting</h2>
  <p>IF is not appropriate for everyone. Do not attempt IF if you:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Have a current or past history of an eating disorder (anorexia, bulimia, binge eating disorder) — structured restriction can trigger relapse</li>
    <li>Are pregnant or breastfeeding — calorie and nutrient needs are elevated and should not be restricted</li>
    <li>Have type 1 diabetes or take insulin — fasting creates serious hypoglycaemia risk without medical supervision</li>
    <li>Are under 18 — growing bodies require consistent nutrient supply</li>
    <li>Have a BMI below 18.5 — you should not be in a calorie deficit</li>
    <li>Take medications that must be taken with food — consult your doctor first</li>
    <li>Have a history of fainting, hypoglycaemia, or adrenal issues</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If you have any chronic health condition, check with your doctor before starting IF. This is especially important if you take any regular medication.</p>

  <h2 id="getting-started">How to Get Started With 16:8</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Choose your eating window.</strong> 12pm–8pm is the most common. Pick one that fits your lifestyle — consistency matters more than the specific hours.</li>
    <li><strong>Start with 12:12.</strong> If 16 hours feels too long initially, begin with 12 hours fasting and gradually extend by one hour per week.</li>
    <li><strong>Stay hydrated during the fasting window.</strong> Water, black coffee, and plain tea are allowed and help suppress hunger.</li>
    <li><strong>Find your calorie target.</strong> Use our <a href="/calorie-calculator">Calorie Calculator</a> to determine maintenance calories, then aim to eat 300–500 kcal below that within your window.</li>
    <li><strong>Hit your protein target.</strong> Calculate your target with our <a href="/macro-calculator">Macro Calculator</a> and make sure protein-rich foods anchor every meal.</li>
    <li><strong>Add resistance training.</strong> Aim for 3 sessions per week of weights or bodyweight exercises to preserve muscle during the deficit.</li>
    <li><strong>Give it 4 weeks.</strong> The first 1–2 weeks often involve hunger and adjustment. Most people find hunger decreases significantly after the body adapts.</li>
  </ol>


  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>Quick summary:</strong> Intermittent fasting is a proven, sustainable approach to weight loss for many people — but it works through calorie reduction, not metabolic magic. Choose a protocol that fits your lifestyle, hit your protein target within the eating window, and add resistance training to preserve muscle. The best fasting approach is the one you can maintain consistently for months.</p>
  </div>

